04284nam a2200601Ia 9780813553375DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135533757 a10.36019/97808135533752doi  a(DE-B1597)529389  a(OCoLC)784885427  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPS1541.Z5 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a811/.41 aWalsh, John Evangelist, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmily Dickinson in Love :bThe Case for Otis Lord /cJohn Evangelist Walsh. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b32 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPROLOGUE: A PUZZLEMENT -- tI. THE UNMASKING -- tII. THE LOVE AFFAIR -- tAPPENDICES -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes and Sources -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tIndex to Poems0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the award-winning author of Poe the Detective: The Curious Circumstances Behind "The Mystery of Marie Roget" comes a compelling argument for the identity of Emily Dickinson’s true love Proud of my broken heart Since thou didst break it, Proud of the pain I Did not feel till thee . . . Those words were written by Emily Dickinson to a married man. Who was he? For a century or more the identity of Emily Dickinson’s mysterious “Master” has been eagerly sought, especially since three letters from her to him were found and published in 1955. In Emily Dickinson in Love, John Evangelist Walsh provides the first book-length treatment of this fascinating subject, offering a solution based wholly on documented facts and the poet’s own writings. Crafting the affair as a love story of rare appeal, and writing with exquisite attention to detail, in Part I Walsh reveals and meticulously proves the Master to be Otis Lord, a friend of the poet’s father and a man of some reputation in law and politics. Part II portrays the full dimensions of their thirty-year romance, most of it clandestine, including a series of secret meetings in Boston. After uncovering and confirming the Master’s identity, Walsh fits that information into known events of Emily’s life to make sense of facts long known but little understood—Emily’s decision to dress always in white, for instance, or her extreme withdrawal from a normal existence when she had previously been an active, outgoing friend to many men and women. In a lengthy section of Notes and Sources, Walsh presents his proofs in abundant detail, demonstrating that the evidence favors one man so irresistibly that there is left no room for doubt. Each reader will decide if he has truly succeeded in making the case for Otis Lord.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPoets, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355337540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553375423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813553375/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles